li.p:
Let L(t) represent the company's total sales t years after starting business, where t = 0 is the first year of operation. If sales grow linearly, then L(t) has the form L(t) = b + mt. Now L(0) = 80,000, so the intercept b is 80,000. The slope m of the graph is
\frac{\Delta S}{\Delta t}= \frac{8000 \text{ dollars}}{1\text{ year}}= 8000 \text{ dollars/year}
where \Delta S = 8000 is the increase in sales during the first year. Thus, L(t) = 80,000 + 8000t, and sales grow by adding $8000 each year. The expected sales total for the next year is L(2) = 80,000 + 8000(2) = 96,000
